GS: We have consistently argued that the market reaction to the debt ceiling debate itself is really quite irrelevant. The important topic is the evolution of market liquidity post-debt ceiling resolution, and the wave of Treasury bill issuance that follows in order to rebuild the Treasury General Account (TGA). It is really impossible to know where the required liquidity will come from to absorb the $600 billion to $1 trillion of issuance. If it comes from the enormous money market fund holdings or RRP balances, then the liquidity squeeze will be much less impactful than if it comes from bank deposits.
